# Introduction

# Background

Government and urban governance projects often develop multiple services and user interfaces (UIs) independently for similar use cases. This leads to:

* **Inconsistent implementations** across services.  
* **Redundant components**, increasing maintenance overhead.  
* **Limited reusability**, requiring teams to build similar features multiple times.

This fragmented approach slows development, complicates scalability, and increases long-term maintenance efforts.

## Purpose

This document proposes a **unified architecture** that consolidates common services, UIs, and configurations into a **reusable and scalable framework**. By introducing:

* A **common service layer** to standardize logic and reduce duplication.  
* A **configurable UI** to adapt services without separate implementations.  
* A **centralized management console** for easier customization and control.

## Key Benefits

‚úÖ **Reduces redundancy** by eliminating duplicate services and UIs.  
 ‚úÖ **Improves maintainability** with standardized implementations.  
 ‚úÖ **Enhances scalability** with configurable services.  
 ‚úÖ **Optimizes development efforts** through a shared framework.

## Goals of the Solution Framework

1. Reduce the time for build of a particular use case. As a reference point, we will pick up two use cases \- License and Permits and Grievance Redressal.   
2. Reduce configuration time for a particular use case. Configuration would include changing the form fields, workflows, users and roles and adding master data.

## Scope

This document covers:

* Current challenges in managing multiple services and UIs.  
* A proposed solution using a **shared service layer**, a **generic UI**, and **config-driven customization**.  
* Technical design, architecture, and deployment strategies.  
* Security, performance, and scalability considerations.  
* A roadmap for future improvements.

By adopting this approach, government services can improve efficiency, consistency, and cost-effectiveness.

**Limitations** in the first version **:**

* Not all urban products can be fully implemented.  
* Solutions like OBPAS, which involve multiple workflows, cannot be supported   
* A table within the UI cannot be integrated directly into a form.

# Problem Statement

Currently, multiple independent services and UIs are built separately for similar use cases, leading to:

‚ùå **Duplicated Efforts** ‚Äì Teams rebuild similar services instead of reusing existing ones.  
 ‚ùå **Inconsistent Logic** ‚Äì Each service is implemented differently, making standardization difficult.  
 ‚ùå **High Maintenance Costs** ‚Äì Every service requires independent updates and bug fixes.  
 ‚ùå **Scalability Issues** ‚Äì Managing multiple versions creates operational complexity.  
 ‚ùå **Limited Reusability** ‚Äì A lack of shared components leads to inefficiencies.

## 

## 

## Solution Approach

To address these challenges, we propose:

* A **Common Service Layer** to centralize service logic.  
* A **Configurable UI** that adapts based on service requirements.  
* A **Management Console** for easy customization and control.

This solution streamlines development, simplifies maintenance, and enhances scalability.

---

# Proposed Solution: Common Solution Framework

To improve efficiency and reduce redundancy, we introduce a **Common Solution Framework**

 built on **Digit Core Services**.

## Key Components

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Generic Service

Handles **requests, validations, and data aggregation** across modules.

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Application Service

Manages **workflows and business logic**, extendable via **configuration**.

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Transformer Service

Processes and **formats data** for integration with other systems.

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Registry Service

Stores **approved applications** and integrates existing records.

### 5 Dynamic Module Creation

New modules can be added via:  
 üîπ **Admin Console** ‚Äì UI-based module creation.  
 üîπ **Configuration** ‚Äì Enables modules without code changes.

## Benefits

‚úÖ **Simplifies frontend interactions** by centralizing logic.  
 ‚úÖ **Reduces redundancy & maintenance** through reuse.  
 ‚úÖ **Supports rapid module deployment** via configuration.  
 ‚úÖ **Ensures consistent data flow** across services.

This approach makes development **faster, scalable, and easier to maintain**.

# System Architecture Overview

The system follows a **modular, service-oriented architecture** designed to:  
 ‚úî **Streamline frontend interactions** with a unified API layer.  
 ‚úî **Optimize backend communication** by reducing direct dependencies.  
 ‚úî **Ensure extensibility** through configuration-driven service creation.

## Common Services

### **1Ô∏è‚É£ Generic Service (Orchestrator)**

* Acts as the **central entry point** for all frontend interactions.  
* Manages **request routing, validation, and response aggregation** across core services.  
* Reduces **direct dependencies** on multiple backend services, ensuring a **simplified API layer**.  
* Supports **dynamic module creation** through configuration, enabling flexible service activation.  
* **Initializes required data** for dependent core services to ensure seamless integration.  
* Provides a **default calculator** for simple use cases.

### **Core Services Integrated with the Orchestrator**

‚úÖ **MDMS (Master Data Management System)**  
 ‚úÖ **Individual Service**  
 ‚úÖ **Workflow Service**  
 ‚úÖ **PDF Generation Service**  
 ‚úÖ **SMS & Notification Service**  
 ‚úÖ **Localization Service**  
 ‚úÖ **File Storage (Filestore) Service**  
 ‚úÖ **Boundary Service**  
 ‚úÖ **ID Generation Service**  
 ‚úÖ **Authorization Service**  
 ‚úÖ **Billing & Payment Service**

---

### **2Ô∏è‚É£ Application Service**

* Manages **business logic** and orchestrates workflows based on workflow configurations.  
* Provides **APIs for frontend interactions** and internal service communication.  
* Supports **modular and extensible service development**, minimizing code modifications.  
* Handles **dynamic field management**, adapting to specific use cases via configuration.  
* Can be **extended to support new urban governance modules** without additional development.

---

### **3Ô∏è‚É£ Transformer Service (Planned for Future Release)**

* Processes and structures data from various sources by:  
   üîπ Adding **approved, validated data** to the registry.  
   üîπ Retrieving **structured data** as needed.  
   üîπ Normalizing and transforming data formats for consistency.  
* Reduces **transformation logic** in the Generic or Application Service, improving maintainability.  
* Uses a **configuration-driven approach** to define transformation rules dynamically.  
* Will function based on **configurations for data fetching and transferring**.  
* This service is **planned for a future release** and may not be available in the first beta version.

---

### **4Ô∏è‚É£ Record/Registry Service**

* Acts as a **persistent data layer**, reducing redundant API calls and improving efficiency.  
* Once an **application is approved**, it is stored in the registry as a **validated record**.  
* Supports **triggering new transactions** based on stored records.  
* If an **external registry is available**, data can be pushed to it.  
* If no external registry is required, this service serves as the **default registry** for the application.

---

###   **5** Generic UI

* A **configuration-driven UI** that dynamically adapts based on service configurations.  
* Supports **dynamic forms, workflows, and screens**, tailored to specific service needs.  
* Enables a **seamless flow** from service application to approval and tracking.

---

### **6 Console (Planned for Future Release)**

* A **low-code/no-code** platform for dynamically configuring and modifying services.  
* Enables users to **create, initialize, and manage services** with minimal development effort.  
* Facilitates **rapid deployment and customization** of services.  
* Should include **separate configurators** for **localization message handling, workflows, SMS, and MDMS data**.  
* Currently, the console is **focused solely on service enablement**. Handling of **localization, workflows, SMS, and MDMS** may be integrated in future updates.  
* Integration of multiple modules \- for example, property being referenced in the business license module.

## Configuration

This configuration file defines the **service configuration for Trade License (Tradelicence)** under the **CommonService** module in an MDMS (Master Data Management System). Below is a breakdown of its key sections:

---

### **1\. General Information**

* **`tenantId`:** `"pg"` ‚Üí The tenant or jurisdiction the configuration applies to.

* **`moduleName`:** `"CommonService"` ‚Üí Indicates that this configuration is part of the common services.

---

### **2\. Service Details (`ServiceConfiguration`)**

This section defines the **Trade License service** and its various configurations.

#### **2.1 Fields Configuration**

This defines the different attributes required for trade licenses:

* Each field has a `name`, `label`, `type`, and `reference`.

* Some fields depend on others (e.g., `tradeStructureSubType` depends on `tradeStructureType`).

* **Trade Name (`tradeName`) has validations:**

  * Length (2-128 characters)

  * Regex validation (`^[A-Za-z0-9 ]+$`) ‚Äì allows only letters, numbers, and spaces.

  * Mandatory field (`isRequired: true`).

---

### **3\. Workflow Configuration**

Defines the workflow stages:

* **`businessService`:** `"NewTL"` (Trade License application process).

* **`ACTIVE` status:** `"APPROVED"` ‚Üí License is approved.

* **`INACTIVE` statuses:** `"REJECTED"`, `"WITHDRAWN"` ‚Üí License is rejected or withdrawn.

---

### **4\. Fee Calculation (`calculator`)**

Defines billing slabs:

* `applicationFee`: **‚Çπ2000** is the base fee for applying.

---

### **5\. ID Generation (`idgen`)**

* Trade license application numbers follow the format: `"tl.application.number"`.

---

### **6\. Localization (`localization`)**

* Uses localization from the `"digit-tradelicence"` module.

---

### **7\. Notifications (`notification`)**

* SMS and email notifications exist but are not yet defined (`"TODO"` placeholders).

---

### **8\. Access Control (`access`)**

* **Roles:** `"TL_CREATOR"` has access.

* **Actions:** The only defined action is calling `tl-services/v1/create`.

---

### **9\. Rules & Validations (`rules`)**

Defines different types of rules for:

* **Validation (`schema`, `api`, `custom`, or `none`).**

* **Fee Calculation (`api`, `custom`, or `none`).**

* **Registry handling (`api` or `none`).**

* **References:** The `"initiate"` service triggers `tradelicence`.

---

### **10\. Document Requirements (`documents`)**

Defines documents needed for application:

1. **Address Proof:** Aadhaar, Voter ID (optional).

2. **Identity Proof:** Aadhaar, Voter ID (mandatory).

3. **Owner's Photo:** JPEG, PNG format (mandatory).

**Common restrictions:**

* Allowed file types: PDF, DOC, XLS, JPEG, PNG.

* Max file size: **5MB**.

* Max files per category: **1**.

---

### **11\. PDF Configuration (`pdf`)**

Defines PDF documents for:

* **Application:** `"tl-application"`.

* **Bill:** `"tl-bill"`.

* **Receipt:** `"tl-receipt"`.

---

### **12\. Billing (`bill`)**

* Service for handling application fees: `"ApplicationFee"`.

---

### **13\. Payment (`payment`)**

* **Payment gateway:** Placeholder (`"TODO"`, to be configured).

---

### **14\. API Configurations (`apiconfig`)**

Defines API endpoints for:

* **Registering trade licenses (`/tl-services/v1/create`).**

* **Searching trade licenses (`/tl-services/v1/search`).**

* API methods: `POST`.

* Host: Can be **staging (`https://staging.digit.org`)** or **local (`http://tl-services.egov:8080`)**.

---

### **15\. Applicant Rules (`applicant`)**

* Minimum **1** and maximum **3** applicants allowed.

* Applicant types: `"individual"` or `"organisation"`.

---

### **16\. Boundary Configuration (`boundary`)**

* Hierarchy Type: `"REVENUE"`.

* Lowest boundary level: `"locality"`.

---

### **17\. Enabling Access (`enabled`)**

* Available for **citizen** and **employee** users.

---

## **Implementation Strategy**

### **Phase 1: Core Service Development & UI Integration (Beta Release)**

‚úÖ Develop **Generic Service (Orchestrator)** for request routing, Initialise data and response aggregation.

 ‚úÖ Build **Application Service** to handle workflow-based business logic.

 ‚úÖ Implement **Registry Service** for persistent validated records.

 ‚úÖ Develop **Generic UI** to support **dynamic forms and workflows**.

### **Phase 2: Data Processing & Optimization**

 ‚úÖ Create **Console for service configuration**.

‚úÖ Introduce **Transformer Service** for **data Normalization and Transformation to Support Integrating with Existing Registries**.

 ‚úÖ Implement **Config-driven transformation rules** for flexible data processing.

 ‚úÖ Optimize **performance** by reducing redundant data processing in UI & backend.

### **Phase 3: External System Integrations & Advanced Features**

‚úÖ Enable **external registry integration** for organizations needing third-party data storage.

 ‚úÖ Expand **workflow customization** capabilities within the Console.

 ‚úÖ Introduce **advanced audit logging and history tracking** in the Registry Service.

---

## **Expected Benefits**

üîπ **Scalability** ‚Äì Configuration-based modular architecture supports adding new services without major code changes.  
 üîπ **Flexibility** ‚Äì Dynamic workflows, UI, and data processing adapt to different service needs.  
 üîπ **Performance Optimization** ‚Äì Persistent data storage and transformation services reduce API redundancy.  
 üîπ **Ease of Maintenance** ‚Äì Low-code/no-code approach simplifies service modification and deployment.  
 üîπ **Seamless Frontend Interaction** ‚Äì A unified API gateway ensures efficient data retrieval and request handling.
